  "prompt": "Do I have to pay VAT if my company is registered outside the EU, but my bank is in Latvia (in EU)?",
  "response": "Whether you need to pay VAT on transactions involving a company registered outside the EU depends on a variety of factors, including the nature of the goods or services being provided, where the transaction takes place, and the VAT laws of the specific EU country involved.\n\n1. **Goods**: If you're importing goods into the EU from a non-EU country, VAT is typically due at the point of entry. This means that even if your company is registered outside the EU, if you are bringing goods into Latvia, you will generally need to pay VAT on those goods.\n\n2. **Services**: The treatment of VAT on services can be more complex. Generally, if a non-EU entity provides services to an EU business, the place of taxation is typically where the business receiving the service is located. If your company provides services to clients in the EU, you may not need to charge VAT, but you'll need to comply with the local VAT laws in Latvia.\n\n3. **Bank Transactions**: Having a bank in Latvia does not inherently change your VAT obligations. Your VAT liability will depend more on the nature of your transactions rather than your banking arrangements.\n\nFor precise guidance tailored to your specific situation, particularly as VAT regulations can be complex and vary by case, it's advisable to consult with a tax professional or VAT expert familiar with both EU regulations and the particular circumstances of your business.",
